name: WAVE DIVISION [AQUATIC]
description:
Rap dudes on that trill wave. Rock(ish) heads on that chill wave. Scientist cats on that particle wave. Hawaiian cats surfin' on them tsunami waves. Dope boys on that coke wave. We all made of water, so really we on the same wave if you think about it. Shoutout to my lil homey the moon.

Special underwater colorway, in a limited edition of 50. For everyone, struggling on land, wishing they were in the water. Keep your head up.

name: THANK YOU BASED GOD
description: There's that old poem about footprints in the sand and God. The idea being that God is always chilling beside you and when you're at your worst he's carrying you. Some of us like to think that the Based God is with us at all times. This means that when you're swagless, not thinking positively, or too tired to fuck your bitch—the Based God is there to carry you. Wear this joint and show your appreciation to the pretty bitch.

name: GUNPLAY (RAP GAME BURZUM)
description:
Gunplay has called himself a "human L.A. riot", threatened to cancel christmas, and has a weird fascination with WW2. With that love of violence, hatred for Christianity, and interest in Panzer attacks; dude could easily be the first rapper that could be down with black metal* bands. Plus, he's a "white bitch carnivore", pretty sure there's a ton of them in Norway. 

<sup>*Black metal like Burzum or Marduk, not black metal like Suffocation.</sup>

description: Celebrate your love of the uniting force of all brutal music, the blast beat. From grind to black metal to death metal nothing says unrelenting ferocity like a good old fashion 300bpm blast beat. Now you can let the world know you're tired of their shit and rather be listening to Dying Fetus' Kill Your Mother/Rape Your Dog. Limited Edition of 125 behold the destroyer

name: QUOTATIONS FROM CASH MONEY
description: A short book of stories, essays, and theories about one of the greatest labels ever to put raps to wax: Cash Money Records. Look at the work, jewelry and philosophies of Juvenile, Lil' Wayne, Baby, B.G. & The Great Man Mannie Fresh. Like those lil Watchtower joints Jehovah's Witnesses try to sell you on the corner, but instead of being about the bible this is about 400 Degrees and Hood RIch. This book concerns itself with what we can learn about the world and ourselves through the work of Cash Money. Chapters include: - 9 Cash Money Songs To Play At Your Funeral - Ass Telepathy - The Creation Of Lil Wayne—The Greatest Rapper Alive—By Baby, Amateur Child Psychologist - A Magical Incantation of Ass In Three Parts - Controlling All The Seafood Trade In New England: Materialism As Defiance and more... Read an excerpt here. May Fresh be with you. * There are no mentions of No Limit Records in this book. As much as I respect the next level statement that is a functional gold tank, my strong allegiance to Cash Money prevents me from even comparing and contrasting the two labels.

name: TAROT DE LES VICIEUX PAROLIERS V: THE HIEROPHANT/GHOSTFACE
description: Dimensions: 18"W X 24"H Material: Epson Cold Press Watercolor Paper Edition of 25 From the ongoing series Tarot De Les Vicieux Paroliers (Tarot Of The Vicious Lyricists) combining rappers and archetypes from the tarot. Card five is The Hierophant/Ghostface. The Hierophant card represents wisdom, maturity, tradition and respect of the group. If there's an elder statesman in rap that's still respected and relevant it has to be Ghostface. He serves the role of your crazy/frank uncle who can impart knowledge unto you that your parents can't. Ghost is the uncle who would give you a porno at 14, teach you how to fight dirty and give you a weighted breakdown on the pros and cons of dating insane women. The Hierophant is a holder of knowledge and thus a holder of the keys to heaven. I'm not entirely sure there's a heaven, but, if there is one I'm pretty sure when you get there Ghostface'll be there making you go to the store for him for all eternity. When you remark that you're now infinite years old and you don't have to go to the store for him anymore he'll simply say "I don't care how old you are you're still my son" - Printed in a limited edition of 25 - Hand signed and numbered - Giclee print on archival, museum quality paper - Shipped rolled in a heavyweight tube

name: TAROT DE LES VICIEUX PAROLIERS III: THE EMPRESS/NICKI MINAJ
description: Dimensions: 18"W X 24"H Material: Epson Cold Press Watercolor Paper Edition of 25 From the ongoing series Tarot De Les Vicieux Paroliers (Tarot Of The Vicious Lyricists) combining rappers and archetypes from the tarot. Card three is The Empress/Nicki Minaj. The Empress card represents sexuality, desire, wealth and fertility. The Empress stands as an icon of all feminine power. A symbol of the dominion women's curves, intelligence and intuition gives them over the natural world. The only rapper that could remotely come close to representing all of that would Nicki Minaj. An ever-changing figure that represents women as seen through the male gaze. Nicki is able to change her appearance at will, she's a theatrical performer embodying a multitude of personalities and the spiritual mother to an ever growing army of devoted followers. She also serves as the object of almost every dudes' desire if we can use the discussion at my barbershop as a barometer of such things. - Printed in a limited edition of 25 - Hand signed and numbered - Giclee print on archival, museum quality paper - Shipped rolled in a heavyweight tube

name: TAROT DE LES VICIEUX PAROLIERS XV: THE DEVIL/TYLER, THE CREATOR
description: Dimensions: 18"W X 24"H Material: Epson Cold Press Watercolor Paper Edition of 25 From the ongoing series Tarot De Les Vicieux Paroliers (Tarot Of The Vicious Lyricists) combining rappers and archetypes from the tarot. Card fifteen is The Devil/Tyler, The Creator. The Devil card of the Tarot does not actively represent The Devil as represented in western mythology. The card isn't about corrupting youth, sacrificing woodland creatures or possessing souls. That's more of a Marilyn Manson jumpoff. The Devil card represents passion, anger, obsession, pessimism and the uprooting of social order. Essentially, it represents the plight of the teenager—newly aware of self, full of ideas yet held in impotence by the previous generation. Tyler as the Devil breaks the bondage of society and celebrates the lustful and creative aspects of life. He gives a middle finger to the bonds of conventional society and embraces the freedom of chaos as the only way to live. Or as Tyler succinctly put it "Kill people. Burn shit. Fuck School". - Printed in a limited edition of 25 - Hand signed and numbered - Giclee print on archival, museum quality paper - Shipped rolled in a heavyweight tube

name: TAROT DE LES VICIEUX PAROLIERS XIII: DEATH/WAKA FLOCKA FLAME
description: Dimensions: 18"W X 24"H Material: Epson Cold Press Watercolor Paper Edition of 25 From the ongoing series Tarot De Les Vicieux Paroliers (Tarot Of The Vicious Lyricists) combining rappers and archetypes from the tarot. Card thirteen is Death/Waka Flocka Flame. The Death card represents loss, regeneration and being caught in the inescapable. Listening to Waka's music it's a swirling ball of white hot rage and chaos with musical nods to the apocalypse. There's Waka, screaming unveiled threats of violence, death and chanting his own name like an ancient army calling to their god of war before a battle. All of the violence makes Waka as the Death card seem obvious, but, it goes deeper. The Death card of the Tarot isn't strictly about death in the bodily sense, it concerns death as part of a cycle of regeneration. An end to one thing and the birth of another. Mufasa gets bodied, Simba becomes king. Entropy & enthalpy. Death here is about looking into the unknown and having it transform you. Waka's rage is fueled by bodily death, yet, for him it's become a positive force. There's a full circle of death, conflict and rebirth all contained in the flame. - Printed in a limited edition of 25 - Hand signed and numbered - Giclee print on archival, museum quality paper - Shipped rolled in a heavyweight tube

name: TAROT DE LES VICIEUX PAROLIERS VII: THE CHARIOT/KANYE WEST
description: Dimensions: 18"W X 24"H Material: Epson Cold Press Watercolor Paper Edition of 25 From the ongoing series Tarot De Les Vicieux Paroliers (Tarot Of The Vicious Lyricists) combining rappers and archetypes from the tarot. Card seven is The Chariot/Kanye West. The Chariot is often decried as one of the most difficult to interpret cards of all the Tarot as it's full of contradiction and duality. It symbolizes victory, but the prize may be bitter sweet. It predicts success but warns us to be wary of what we may give up in pursuit of it. This almost too conveniently parallels the career of Kanye West. His music embodies both the low and high brow at the same time. Ballerinas dancing to songs about being a douche bag. Writing curses in cursive. Listening to Wu-Tang trying suits on. If nothing else his work represents the pull of these two opposing worlds and the anguish of living between them. The Chariot cautions against egocentrisim, impulsivity and anxiety. Yet, acknowledges the symbiotic relationship between these personality flaws and the drive to succeed. From his first emergence Kanye's songs have come from a man with no country. He fought hard to win his fame but has maintained a rocky relationship with celebrity. Misunderstood, reviled and cast out, his victory has come in exile. "Do it better than anybody you ever seen do it. Screams from the haters... got a nice ring to it." - Printed in a limited edition of 25 - Hand signed and numbered - Giclee print on archival, museum quality paper - Shipped rolled in a heavyweight tube
